{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513644"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:12:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:12:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12179"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12179","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12179"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.77,0.1,0.03,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4707"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49998"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4707","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4707"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12179"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35251"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"589"},{"type":"tags","id":"1240"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7393"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7641"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13848"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39788"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49998","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49998"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner with a seven day history of abnormal vaginal discharge. She does not have any other symptoms. She is sexually active and has had three male and two female partners in the last three months. She uses the combined oral contraceptive pill and is inconsistent with barrier contraception use for STI prevention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination of the vulva, there are no vesicular lesions or ulcers. On speculum examination an unpleasant odour is noted and there is a small amount of thin white discharge. A high vaginal swab is performed and clue cells are seen on microscopy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the likely organism causing this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Candida albicans","Gardnerella vaginalis","Chlamydia trachomatitis","Neisseria gonorrhea","Treponema pallidum"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Ebacterial vaginosis (BV). This is a polymicrobial dysbiosis characterised by a change from a Lactobacillus dominant state to one with a high degree of anaerobic bacteria including \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EGardnerella vaginalis\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E. Whilst BV is not an STI, increased numbers of sexual partners and lack of barrier contraception use are both significant risk factors. BV is asymptomatic in up to 50% of cases, but in symptomatic patients will present as thin white/grey unpleasant/malodourous discharge. BV is diagnosed using the Amsel criteria which required at least three of the following:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThin white/grey homogenous discharge on speculum examination\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EElevated vaginal pH (pH \u0026gt; 4.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhiff test: malodour with the addition of potassium hydroxide to vaginal secretions, or if not available, genital malodour on examination\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EClue cells on microscopy of Gram stain of high vaginal swab\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the criteria is satisfied, BV is treated with metronidazole 400mg PO for seven days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECandida albicans\u003C/em\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eis a fungal infection that classically presents with white and clumpy odourless discharge.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eis the causative organism of Chlamydia, a bacterial STI which is asymptomatic in 85-90% of patients but can present with dysuria, discharge, pelvic pain, dyspareunia and postcoital bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ENeisseria gonorrhea \u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003Eis the causative organism of gonorrhoea, a bacterial STI which is often symptomatic (80% of cases) but can present with discharge, dysuria, dyspareunia or conjunctivitis\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ETreponema pallidum\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003Cem\u003E \u003C/em\u003Eis the caustive organism of syphilis. Primary syphilis classically presents with a chancre (oral, anal or genital) which is a painless ulcer with a well defined margin and firm base.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bacterial vaginosis is the most likely diagnosis in a patient presenting with thin unpleasant smelling discharge"],"references":["Australian STI Management Guidelines. Bacterial Vaginosis. Available from: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/bacterial-vaginosis/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35251"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12179"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35251","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35251"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-05T16:52:36+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-05T16:53:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4707"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49998"}